Paige - Project Manager at Hendericks Building (Sister)

Paige, age 27. She works in a corporate role earning between $70,000 and $80,000 per year. 
She and her fiance, who earns about $100,000 annually by herself. 
Recently purchased a starter home and are currently planning a wedding that will cost around $35,000. 
They are sharing wedding expenses and receiving some help from family. 
Although their combined income provides stability, Paige feels some financial stress due to the high cost of the wedding and the responsibility of managing a mortgage at the same time.

Paige and her fiance make financial decisions together rather than having one person take full control. 
In the short term, her goal is to complete the wedding without unnecessary debt. 
In the long term, she hopes to move into a larger home, purchase a new car, and eventually start a family. 
She recently has paid off her school debt goal. Because of these goals, understanding where their money goes each month is very important to her future. 
She does not currently use a budgeting app but is highly comfortable with technology, as is her fiance. 
A financial management system that allows shared access, tracks spending categories clearly, and shows progress toward savings goals would help reduce her stress and support their future plans.

Paige user stories:
As a user with monthly and large upcoming expenses, I want to be able to track progress on saving goals.
As a user who is working toward large purchases, and who just finished paying off student loans, 
As a user I want to be able to scale my tracking and change whether expenses are viewed on a daily, weekly, monthly, or yearly scale.
As a user that wants to be open with expenditures with my fiance, I want a shared access system that clearly lays out my expenditures so we are able to save for our future.

User Scenario:
Paige opens MapMyMint while reviewing her monthly finances with her fiance.
With their wedding coming up and new mortgage to manage, she wants to make sure they are staying on track financially.
She navigates to the budgeting dashboard and notices a breakdown of their spending categories, including housing, groceries, and wedding expenses.
After noticing that wedding related spending has grown larger than expected, Paige organizes recent purchases into a "Wedding" category or saving pod.
She then creates a savings goal to track how much they still need to set aside before the wedding.
Being able to clearly see their expenses and progress helps Paige feel more confident managing both their wedding budget and their monthly finances.

Requirement Specification:
The system shall allow Paige and her fiancé to track shared expenses and categorize spending clearly, providing a transparent view of where their money is going each month. 
It shall show progress toward short- and long-term savings goals, such as the wedding, a future home, or a new car, helping them plan without accumulating unnecessary debt. 
The app shall allow secure shared access, generate simple visual summaries, and require minimal manual input while supporting both users in making collaborative financial decisions.
